@node Installation "SmartMedian: Installation"

                                  Installation
                                 --------------

- copy the files from drawer plugins2/ to ArtEffect:plugins2/

- copy the Guide whereever you can retrieve it.

After the next start of ArtEffect2+ the menuentry "SmartMedian VR..." should
be available in Menu Filter/Blur.

@endnode

@node Requirements "SmartMedian: Requirements"

                                  Requirements
                                 --------------

- the only thing you need is ArtEffect2+

@endnode

@node Usage "SmartMedian: Usage"

                                     Usage
                                    -------

   The usage is quite easy, after calling the plugin via menu, you will see a
   little window.

   Just below the preview is a cycle gadget to select wether the plugin should
   work in color or grayscale. Operating in grayscale is faster and will convert
   the picture to gray on-the-fly.

   Radius is the radius around every pixel that will be taken into calculation
   for the actual calculated pixel. E.g. for a Radius of 10 the Matrix has a
   size of 21x21 pixels and is taking 441 surrounding pixels into calculation.

   SmartMedian is doing the same as a normal medianfilter, but does not set the
   the new calculated pixel if it detects a high contrast within the radius.
   A high contrast is a detail or an edge.
   All option influence the decision what a high contrast is and what to do with
   it then.

   Edge Hard
   There are two completly different modes, the first is Hard. When Hard is on,
   any contrast higher than the value set by the Threshold slider is seen as
   high contrast and the pixel will not be set.
   This mode is good for the mentioned (see @{"Introduction" link Introduction}) text on natural
   background thing.

   Edge Soft
   When Soft is on no there is no real border between pixel set and not set.
   All new calculated pixels are mixed with the original pixels weighted by the
   contrast. The lower the contrast the more the new pixelvalue is taken.
   The Threshold slider now varies the transfer function used for the weights.
   This mode is good for denoising natural pictures.

   Note: Simply switching between Hard and Soft doesn't help you much in
         comparing which one of the modes is better for your actual picture,
         because Threshold normally needs different adjustements for both modes.

   Radius:
   Well, as in a normal blur operator, the bigger the radius the blurrier the
   picture gets, BUT in SmartMedian the higher the radius the more likely a 
   high contrast is found and the new pixel is not set.
   For most operations a small amount is probably the better choice.

   Adaptive shrinking
   Allows the radius to be temporally reduced when a high contrast is found.
   SmartMedian tries to shrink the radius until there is no longer the high
   contrast contained in it and then sets the new pixel. Afterwards it proceeds
   with the next pixel and the full radius.
   Adaptive shrinking can slow down the operation enormously.

@endnode

@node Notes "SmartMedian: Notes"

                                     Notes
                                    -------

 - SmartMedian was written on an Amiga 4000 with Cyberstorm MK1 060 and
   compiled with SAS/C 6.58.

 - This PlugIn has no AREXX-Interface and is not localized nor the documentation
   is avaiable in any other language than english (or whatever this is here).
   That may or may not change in the future.

 - If you are interested in getting the information how long an operation took
   try this: setenv VRPLUGINTIMING 1
   

@endnode

